Income and its Implications on Health¶

Collaborators: Rohan Bhatnagar, Nikhil Chandrasekar, Pragadeshwar Kalatheswaran, Dhruva Rayasam

Introduction¶

COVID-19 brought to light the inequality deeply rooted in our society, evident through the emergence of social movements like Black Lives Matter and the National Coalition Against Domestic Violence. As such, the pandemic affected many of us during our formative years in high school and college. Our group, particularly, became more conscious of our health during this time. This inspired us to explore how economics and health intersect, and how an imbalanced wealth distribution factors into health. By looking into aggregate census data (income, records of pre-existing health conditions, health related crime, overdoses, etc.), we spotted an emerging trend around the economic climate of an area and the health of the people occupying it. This caused us to ask questions relating economics and health:

  1. How are income and life expectancy related, and can one be used to predict the other?
  2. How are income and HIV prevalence related, and can one be used to predict the other?
  3. How is the median household income for each county related to the proportion of people with diabetes?

This tutorial outlines how we explored this problem by following the steps of the Data Lifecycle. We begin by curating a dataset and performing an exploratory analysis to understand and identify possible trends that we can investigate. Next, we perform a more intensive primary analysis by using a machine learning model(s) to form predictions on how health and income are related. We will answer the questions posed in earlier and visualize our findings to extract and illustrate key insights. Finally, we will digest and interpret everything we’ve done through the tutorial, and discuss the insights and conclusions, and more importantly, how they affect us.

Data Curation¶

Before we start with this project, it is important to define the scope of the problem we are addressing. For simplicity’s sake, we decided to confine our analysis to the United States, as this would be a much more manageable question to answer and our findings can be extrapolated to many other countries across the globe. Additionally, we wanted to use data from before the pandemic. Covid-19 derailed the way our society functioned, creating huge ripples in the economic and health status of all the people across the world. Using data from the pandemic would make our data too specific and not representative of any other time period, therefore making our analysis useless. Luckily, we were able to find a dataset on Kaggle (link) that contained the data we needed. This data was from 2016, and, as the dataset’s description says, has been “aggregated and filtered from various sources such as the US Census Small Area Income and Poverty Estimates (SAIPE) Program, American Community Survey, CDC National Center for Health Statistics, and more.” This data is split up by county, which is useful for our analysis.

Before we begin analyzing the data, we needed to import a few python libraries to enable us to do the computations required to gain any meaningful insights. There libraries will also be useful for us when we use statistical analysis techniques and machine learning later in the tutorial

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

The next step in the Data Lifecycle is to explore the data and gain a better understanding about it. Our central question revolves around income and its relationship to health, so the majority of our exploratory analysis will be to understand both sides of that question independently, while our primary analysis will be more centered around connecting the two.

1. Is the Median Household Income above the "living wage?"¶

The first thing we will be exploring is the median income for all the counties in our data.

MIT published recently that the livable household income for the average American family (2 adults and 2 children) in 2016 is 15.84 dollars and hour. If both adults are working, this translates to roughly 65,894.4 dollars a year before taxes. We want to see if on average, Americans made more than the “living wage” back in 2016.

To do this, we will be using a hypothesis test, with the null and alternative hypothesis written below. And we will use an alpha level of 0.05

$H_{0}$: $μ_{0}$ = 65894.4

$H_{A}$: $μ_{0}$ ≠ 65894.4

Usually, we would use a t-test, but one of the requirements for this is that the data follow the normal distribution. We can check that by using the .hist() command on the specific column in our dataframe

In [ ]:
df_median_household_income['medianinc'].hist()
# The data doesn't look like it follows the normal distribution,
# so we can't use a t-test. Instead, we will use a non-parametric test
Out[ ]:
<Axes: >

We can see that this data is skewed, so we can’t use a traditional t-test. However, we can use a non-parametric test, specifically a Mann-Whitney U test.

In [ ]:
# Perform Mann-Whitney U test
w, p = wilcoxon(df_median_household_income['medianinc'] - 65894.4)
print("test statistics: ", w)
print("P value: ", p)

test statistics:  5436935.0
P value:  0.0

We get an output of 0 from this test, which means the p value was so low that it got rounded down to 0. Therefore, we can reject the null hypothesis and adopt the alternative hypothesis that the average median household income for all the counties differs from $ 65,894.4.

When doing tests like this, it’s usually a good idea to visualize the results on the histogram itself. In the case of the Mann-Whitney U test, you need to visualize it to get a sense of how different the sample mean is from what you proposed it was. Let’s graph the histogram of median incomes just like we did before, but this time, we will draw a line representing the $ 65,894.4 point on the graph so we can see how much of the data falls on each side. We will use Matplotlib this time. Matplotlib is another Python library, but this one is focused on creating detailed and visually appealing graphs, and we will use this to plot our modified histogram. You can learn more about this library here.

2. Is there a statistically significant difference in median household income between Metropolitan and Nonmetropolitan Areas?¶

We know that there are a lot of counties with a median household income that is below the Living Wage amount, but does whether or not that county is metropolitan or not affect that? We will explore that by looking at the average median incomes (sounds like a weird statement I know) of Metropolitan and Non-metropolitan areas. Once again, we will be using a hypothesis test to assess this.

To compare these two means, we decided to use a two sample t test, with an alpha level of 0.05. The null and alternative hypotheses are written below.

$H_{0}$: There is no statistically significant difference in median household income between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas.

$H_{A}$: There is a statistically significant difference in median household income between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas.

To do this, we assume that the samples are both normally distributed and independent. We can assume independence due to the random sampling required to procure our data, and we can assume the data is normally distributed thanks to the large sample size and the Central Limit Theorem.

We won’t be running this test on the median household income data directly. Instead, we will partition the data into two separate dataframes, one containing the median incomes for metropolitan counties and the other for non-metropolitan counties. We have the code that splits the data and runs the test below.

In [ ]:
metro_incomes = df_median_household_income[df_median_household_income['metro_nonmetro'] == 'Metropolitan']['medianinc']
nonmetro_incomes = df_median_household_income[df_median_household_income['metro_nonmetro'] == 'Nonmetropolitan']['medianinc']

t_value, p_value = ttest_ind(metro_incomes, nonmetro_incomes, equal_var = False)
print("T statistic: ", t_value)
print("P value: ", p_value)

T statistic:  61.374095620194986
P value:  0.0

Because our p-value of approximately 0.0, which is less than our alpha value of 0.05, we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis. The hypothesis test suggests that there is a statistically significant difference in median household income between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas.

To highlight the difference in the means of the median household incomes, we can use visual aids. Specifically, we will be using a bar graph to show the difference between the means in more general terms, and box plots to show the difference in the two distributions.

We will be using Matplotlib again to illustrate this.

In [ ]:
mean_metro = metro_incomes.mean()
mean_nonmetro = nonmetro_incomes.mean()

plt.bar([0,1], [mean_metro, mean_nonmetro], color = 'blue')

plt.show()

It is clear from these two plots that there is indeed a visible difference in the average median household income between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas, which allows us to visually support our conclusion from the two-sample T-test. It’s also good to note that there are a lot of outliers in our data, specifically counties with median incomes much higher than the others. This information will be useful in our further analysis.

3. Comparison of Life Expectancy between Metropolitan and Nonmetropolitan Areas¶

It is clear from these two plots that there is indeed a visible difference in the average median household income between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas, which allows us to visually support our conclusion from the two-sample T-test. It’s also good to note that there are a lot of outliers in our data, specifically counties with median incomes much higher than the others. This information will be useful in our further analysis.

Now that we’ve done our analysis with the classification of a county and its income, we should do the same with some health metric. To spice things up, we can use a Chi-Squared test to do this, and we will be comparing the life expectancy of metropolitan and non-metropolitan areas.

Like before, our alpha is 0.05 and our null and alternative hypothesis are below.

$H_{0}$: There is no statistically significant difference in life expectancy between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas.

$H_{A}$: There is a statistically significant difference in life expectancy between metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas.

In order to do this, we must classify the life expectancy data as either high or low. We can do this with the code above, where we define the threshold between high and low life expectancy as 71, which is 10 years above the retirement age in 2016. We can do that with this code

In [ ]:
threshold = 71
df_life_expectancy['life_expectancy_categorized'] = ['high' if x >= threshold else 'low' for x in df_life_expectancy['life_expectancy']]

We can now run the test on this modified version of the data and graph it using Matplotlib like we did before

In [ ]:
# Chi squared test
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(df_life_expectancy['metro_nonmetro'], df_life_expectancy['life_expectancy_categorized'])
chi2, p_value, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

print("Chi-squared statistic:", chi2)
print("P-value:", p_value)

# Graphing
high = df_life_expectancy[df_life_expectancy['metro_nonmetro'] == 'Nonmetropolitan']['life_expectancy']
low = df_life_expectancy[df_life_expectancy['metro_nonmetro'] == 'Metropolitan']['life_expectancy']

plt.boxplot([high, low], labels = ['Metropolitan', 'Nonmetropolitan'])
plt.title('Comparison of Life Expectancy between Metropolitan and Nonmetropolitan Areas')
plt.ylabel('Life Expectancy (Years)')
plt.grid(axis = 'y')
plt.show()

Chi-squared statistic: 4.251934709862956
P-value: 0.03920564192197968

Given the low p value of about 0.039 (finally a non-zero value) we can reject the null hypothesis and assert that there is a statistically significant difference in life expectancy and county type. By looking at the graph we can see that the range of life expectancies for non-metropolitan areas is much more spread out than that of metropolitan areas, and it appears as if the distribution of the life expectancy in metropolitan areas is shifted slightly to the right when compared to that of non-metropolitan counties.

Overall in this exploratory analysis, we discovered that a majority of these countries have lower median incomes than what is required to live by as per the Living Wage, and that there is a significant difference in median household income and life expectancy across metropolitan and nonmetropolitan areas. We now have a better understanding of the income and health across these counties, which will be helpful in our more involved analysis later on.

Primary Analysis: Question 1 (Relationship between income and life expectancy)¶

During this phase of the Data lifecycle, we attempt to obtain a predictive model for our data. So we will implement several types of regression models, and pick the one that has the best fit, measured by the r-squared and mean squared error (MSE) metrics. First let's import the necessary libraries. Train-test-split allows us to split our data randomly into training and testing sets. We have also imported some metrics to help us better understand our regression models.

Let's prepare our data and set up our regression models. We will be using both Linear Regression and a Polynomial Fit, as it may better capture complex trends in the data.

In [ ]:
# Prepare data
df_average_medianinc = df_median_household_income.groupby('county_name')['medianinc'].mean().reset_index()
df_income_life_expectancy = pd.merge(df_average_medianinc, df_life_expectancy, on='county_name')

random_state = 42
np.random.seed(random_state)

medianinc_array = df_income_life_expectancy['medianinc'].to_numpy()
life_expectancy_array = df_income_life_expectancy['life_expectancy'].to_numpy()

# initialize training and test sets
income_train, income_test, life_expectancy_train, life_expectancy_test = train_test_split(
    medianinc_array, life_expectancy_array, test_size=0.25, random_state=random_state)

The lines look fitted, and we can see the the polynomial fit captures the curved increase at higher median incomes. This is reflected in the r^2 value, as the polynomial fit has a higher value than the linear regression. We can also see that the MSE is quite high for both, which makes sense, as there is a lot of residual error and the data is widely distributed across every income.

The above plots show the results of a linear regression model using both a line of best fit and polynomial feature with degree = 3 to predict life expectancy based on median income. The scatter plots represent the data points, with blue indicating entries in the training set, and green indicating entries of the test set. There are two lines of best fit, one formed from each dataset. The model captures a moderate positive relationship between the two categories, indicated by a postivie R-squared (R²) value. This indicates that a higher income is typically associated with higher life expectancy.

The R-squared (R²) value is 0.3 for the polynomial model, indicating that the model captures about 30% of the variance present in the data.

Primary Analysis: Question 2 (Relationship Between Income and Teen Pregnancy)¶

To answer the question of whether teen pregnancies and income are related, we will use a linear regression with polynomial fit model on the corresponding income and teen pregnancy data. Additionally, to measure the effectiveness of this model we will use MSE and R2 as performance metrics to measure how well our model fits the data.

To measure the relationship between teen pregnancy and income, we must first get the percentage of teen births compared to the female population of that county. We then group median household income and the teen pregnancy rate by county and aggregate by the mean. By performing an inner merge with these two datasets on county_name, we can correspond teen pregnancy rate with the median income for each county.

In [ ]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
import pandas as pd
from sklearn.metrics import mean_squared_error, r2_score

# prepare the data

df_teen_births['births_perc'] = df_teen_births['births_15_to_19'] / df_teen_births['female_population_15_to_19']

df_average_medianinc = df_median_household_income.groupby('county_name')['medianinc'].mean().reset_index()
df_avg_pregnancies = df_teen_births.groupby('county_name')['births_perc'].mean().reset_index()

df_inc_preg = pd.merge(df_average_medianinc, df_avg_pregnancies, on=['county_name'], how='inner')

medianinc_array = df_inc_preg['medianinc'].to_numpy()

The plot above visually demonstrates the relationship between income and teen pregnancy rates, averaged across counties. The blue data points represent training data while the green represents test data. The red line demonstrates the fitted line for training data and the orange line demonstrates a fitted line for test data.

To generate these fitted models, a linear regression model and linear regression model with polynomial features were used. For our performance metrics, we used MSE (Mean Squared Error) and R2 to measure the effectiveness of our model. For the regression model using polynomial fitting, the test/train MSE values are 0.00018 and 0.00019 respectively, suggesting that there is low error between the predicted and actual data. The R2 value is also 0.45 and 0.35 for the test and train datasets, suggesting that there is a moderately strong relationship between median income and teen pregnancy rates. For the linear model, the MSE for the train and test folds were 0.000215 and 0.000207, while the R2 values were 0.30 and 0.38 respectively. This suggests that the polynomial model fits the data more accurately, as shown by the lower MSE values and higher R2 values.

It also demonstrates that the independent variable (income) explains 45% of the variance for the test data and 35% of the variance in the training data. Specifically, we can see from the plot that teen pregnancy has a negative correlation with median income, such that the percentage of teen pregnancies with respect to female population decreases as median income increases.

Though the model fits the data somewhat well, the gap in metrics between training and testing may suggest an overfit model; going forward, being conscious of this effect may be useful in preventing an overfit model that captures the noise in the data rather than the underlying patterns.

The two plots above showcase the results of polynomial regression models of different degrees, linear and cubic, aimed at predicting the diabetes percentage based on the median household income in U.S. counties. The first plot, which employs linear regression with polynomial features, displays the training data as blue dots and the testing data as green dots, with the fitted lines for each set shown in red and orange, respectively. The model's performance, indicated by a Mean Squared Error (MSE) of 0.0003 for the training set and 0.0002 for the testing set, along with R² values of 0.3249 and 0.3375, suggests that the linear model explains around 32-34% of the variance in the data. The second plot uses a cubic regression model, similarly visualizing the training and testing data points and their corresponding fitted lines. The cubic model shows an improved fit, with MSE values of 0.0002 for both sets and R² values of 0.3931 and 0.3621, indicating that the cubic model captures the relationship better, explaining around 36-39% of the variance. Both models reveal a negative correlation between median income and diabetes percentage, with higher income generally associated with a lower diabetes rate. The cubic regression model, however, fits the data more accurately, highlighting the importance of selecting an appropriate polynomial degree to capture non-linear relationships. Additionally, the close performance metrics between the training and testing sets in both models suggest effective generalization without significant overfitting.

Conclusion¶

In the last part of the life cycle, we are to analyze our findings to extract some meaning from what we’ve done as a whole. We set out to see if there was a relationship between income and health, and using machine learning and data analysis techniques, we were able to reach some conclusions. Health is an arbitrary concept, so we put it in more definitive terms by comparing income to life expectancy, teen pregnancy, and diabetes prevalence. That way, we can assess people’s health conditions with life expectancy and diabetes prevalence, and we can use teen pregnancy as a way of analyzing the health infrastructure in the area. Throughout our analysis, we’ve seen that there is some correlation between income and health, with varying levels of strength across indicators for the health of a county. It’s very obvious that money is not spread equally across all people, and as a result of this data lifecycle tutorial, we now know that unequal funds lead to unequal health statuses.
